## How each requirement is satisfied

| # | Requirement | Implementation |
|---|-------------|----------------|
| 1 | Search input at top | `<input type="search" …>` rendered before the list |
| 2 | Custom 300 ms debounce, no lodash | `useDebounce` hook using `setTimeout` / `useEffect` |
| 3 | Case-insensitive substring match on `name` | `.toLowerCase().includes(queryForFilter.toLowerCase())` |
| 4 | "Searching…" during debounce delay | Shown when `rawQuery !== '' && rawQuery !== activeQuery` |
| 5 | Empty input → show all items | `queryForFilter = rawQuery === '' ? '' : activeQuery` bypasses the debounce on clear |
| 6 | Highlight matches with `<mark>` | `highlightMatch` splits on a capturing regex; odd-indexed parts are the matches |
| 7 | "No results found" message | Rendered when `!isSearching && filteredItems.length === 0` |
| 8 | Cleanup on unmount | `return () => clearTimeout(timer)` in the `useEffect` destructor |
| 9 | Whitespace-only = empty; no regex errors | `.trim()` on both sides; `escapeRegex` sanitises the pattern before `new RegExp(…)` |

### Key design decisions

- **`rawQuery` vs `activeQuery`** — Two normalised views of the input. `rawQuery` is used for immediate "is empty?" checks; `activeQuery` is the debounced value used for actual filtering and highlight rendering.
- **Instant clear** — Resetting the input (`rawQuery === ''`) immediately flushes `queryForFilter` to `''` so the full list re-appears without a 300 ms delay, which feels snappier and prevents a lingering "Searching…" flash.
- **List visibility during debounce** — The list stays visible and shows the *last settled* results while the user is still typing, avoiding a jarring disappear/reappear cycle.
- **Capturing group split trick** — `"Hello World".split(/(World)/i)` → `["Hello ", "World", ""]`. Because a single capturing group is used, matched substrings always land at **odd indices**, making the highlight logic a simple `i % 2 === 1` check.

